        "text": "*[Bug 18745] format(&lt;data.frame&gt;) does not keep `_NA_character` column names*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=18745>\n\n--- Comment #4 from Sebastian Meyer (<mailto:seb.meyer@fau.de|seb.meyer@fau.de>) ---\nNot sure about back-porting. Now, for `as.data.frame(&lt;list&gt;, col.names=)` and\nif all list elements produce exactly one column in the result, the default\n`check.names` and `fix.empty.names` tweaks are no longer active, for example:\n\n```\nas.data.frame(list(1), col.names = \"var 1\")  |&gt; names()\n```\n\ngave \"var.1\" but now gives \"var 1\", whereas\n\n```\nas.data.frame(list(cbind(1,2)), col.names = \"var 1\")  |&gt; names()\n```\n\ngives `c(\"var.1.1\", \"var.1.2\")`.\nMaybe the replacement should focus on the `<http:\/\/is.na|is.na>(col.names)` cases.\n\nI see that the patch also added a `new.names` argument as a new feature. I\nwonder how useful that is (I'm a bit confused about its purpose). It would not\nbe clear to me that this would need to be specified to retain the NA name in\n`as.data.frame(setNames(list(1), NA_character_), optional = TRUE)`. Maybe the\n&lt;NA&gt; should be kept automatically in the \"optional\" case? For comparison,\nconverting a matrix with a missing column name does preserve that missingness\n(because it does not really check.names anyway):\n\n```\nas.data.frame(matrix(1, dimnames=list(NULL, NA_character_)))\n##   &lt;NA&gt;\n## 1    1\n```",
